Les Misérables is a 1995 film written and directed by Claude Lelouch. Set in France during the first half of the 20th century, it concerns a poor and illiterate man Henri Fortin (Jean-Paul Belmondo) who is introduced to Victor Hugo's classic novel Les Misérables and begins to see parallels between it and his own life.The director cast his daughter Salomé and gave her character her name.The film won the 1995 Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film and Annie Girardot won the 1996 César Award for Best Supporting Actress.